{"result":{"contents":[{"language":"java","value":"org.junit.Ignore"},"Sometimes you want to temporarily disable a test or a group of tests. Methods annotated with org.junit.Test that are also annotated with `@Ignore` will not be executed as tests. Also, you can annotate a class containing test methods with `@Ignore` and none of the containing tests will be executed. Native JUnit 4 test runners should report the number of ignored tests along with the number of tests that ran and the number of tests that failed.\r\n\r\nFor example:\r\n\r\n    @Ignore @Test public void something() { ...\r\n\r\n@Ignore takes an optional default parameter if you want to record why a test is being ignored:\r\n\r\n    @Ignore(\"not ready yet\") @Test public void something() { ...\r\n\r\n@Ignore can also be applied to the test class:\r\n\r\n    @Ignore public class IgnoreMe {\n              @Test public void test1() { ... }\n              @Test public void test2() { ... }\n             }\r\n\r\n *  **Since:**\r\n    \r\n     *  4.0"]},"id":"12464","type":"vertex","label":"hoverResult"}
